# Riverpod — codegen

## Approach

Riverpod 3.0 + `riverpod_generator`. `@riverpod` annotation on classes and functions.
No manual `Provider<T>((ref) => ...)`, no `ChangeNotifierProvider`, no `StateNotifierProvider` (legacy API).

**Domain stays pure** — Use Case classes live in `domain/usecases/` with no Riverpod. Their providers live in `di/`.

## Ref

Generic `Ref` only. No named typed ref (`GameNotifierRef`, etc.) — deprecated since 2.6.0, removed in 3.0.

## Where providers live

| Provider | Location |
| --- | --- |
| Use Case | `features/<feature>/di/<use_case>_provider.dart` |
| Repository / DataSource | `features/<feature>/di/` or `data/` |
| Notifier | `presentation/notifiers/<feature>_notifier.dart` |
| Navigation | `features/<feature>/di/` or `navigation/` |
| Runtime (SharedPreferences, Talker) | `core/providers/` |
| GoRouter | `app/router.dart` |

One `@riverpod` function per file. No central `providers.dart` barrel.

## Use Cases (`di/`)

```dart
// di/play_move_use_case_provider.dart — pure use case, no repository
@riverpod
PlayMoveUseCase playMoveUseCase(Ref ref) => const PlayMoveUseCase();

// di/save_game_use_case_provider.dart — depends on repository abstraction
@riverpod
SaveGameUseCase saveGameUseCase(Ref ref) {
  return SaveGameUseCase(ref.watch(gameRepositoryProvider));
}

// di/start_game_use_case_provider.dart — cross-feature via domain abstraction
@riverpod
StartGameUseCase startGameUseCase(Ref ref) {
  return StartGameUseCase(ref.watch(settingsRepositoryProvider));
}

```

## Notifier

One Notifier per file, in `presentation/notifiers/<feature>_notifier.dart`.

```dart
@riverpod
class GameNotifier extends _$GameNotifier {
  @override
  GameState build() {
    return const GameState.initial();
  }

  void playMove(int cellIndex) {
    final result = ref.read(playMoveUseCaseProvider).execute(
      game: state.game,
      cellIndex: cellIndex,
    );
    state = switch (result) {
      Success(:final value) => state.copyWith(game: value),
      Failure(:final error) => state.copyWith(error: error),
    };
  }
}
```

Rules:

- `build()` handles initialization, never the constructor.
- The Notifier calls Use Cases, never inline business logic.
- Exposed state always immutable (`freezed` for states with multiple fields).

## Repositories (`di/`)

```dart
@riverpod
GameRepository gameRepository(Ref ref) {
  return LocalGameRepository(
    ref.watch(gameLocalDataSourceProvider),
  );
}

```

## Navigation

Navigation impl receives `GoRouter` via provider injection:

```dart
@riverpod
GameNavigation gameNavigation(Ref ref) {
  return GameNavigationImpl(ref.watch(routerProvider));
}
```

## Naming

- File: `<name>_provider.dart` in `di/`, `<feature>_notifier.dart` in notifiers
- Generated provider: `<name>Provider` (auto, do not rename manually)
- Use Dart 3 interface classes for repositories and navigation.

Prefer:

`abstract interface class GameRepository`

Avoid:

`abstract class IGameRepository`

## DI Rules

- `ref.watch`: reactive dependencies (repositories, use cases, router, navigation)
- `ref.read`: one-shot read inside Notifier callbacks/methods
- No business logic in a provider body — wiring only

## Forbidden

```dart
// ❌ @riverpod inside domain/usecases/
// domain/usecases/play_move_use_case.dart must NOT import riverpod_annotation

// ❌ core provider redeclared inside a feature
@riverpod
SharedPreferences sharedPreferences(Ref ref) { ... } // must live in core/

// ❌ importing another feature's notifier or view
import 'package:tictactoe/features/settings/presentation/notifiers/settings_notifier.dart';

```

## Runtime providers

Async runtime dependencies (persistence, env) are initialized in `appStartupProvider` (`keepAlive: true`). Dependent sync providers read from startup via `ref.watch(appStartupProvider).requireValue`.

```dart
@Riverpod(keepAlive: true)
Future<SharedPreferences> appStartup(Ref ref) async {
  return SharedPreferences.getInstance();
}

@riverpod
SharedPreferences sharedPreferences(Ref ref) {
  return ref.watch(appStartupProvider).requireValue;
}
```

In tests, override `sharedPreferencesProvider` (or `appStartupProvider`) via `overrideWithValue` — no need to call `main()`.

## Testing

Every provider mockable via `overrideWith` / `overrideWithValue` in `ProviderContainer.test()` (Riverpod 3.0) or `ProviderScope(overrides: [...])` for widget tests.
